Abstract¶

The Eastern coyote has become ubiquitous throughout New York State, recently being documented breeding on Long Island, the last region of the state thought to be without them. Using ArcGIS Pro, python and procedures established in U.S Fish & Wildlife ESM 103 I created a predictive Habitat Suitability Model (HSM) to assist with future research and management efforts.

Background¶

The Eastern coyote is larger than it's Western cousin typically reaching weights of 30 to 40 pounds and heights up to 24 inches. It was long suspected and more recentely confirmed that Eastern coyotes are the result of hybridization with wolves & dogs. Additionally, less plentiful resources in north eastern forest areas partially cause larger size in Eastern coyotes as they seek larger prey more often (e.g. White Tail Deer) (Gompper 2002; Way & Lynn 2016). Being a relatively large mid-sized mesocarnivore with a wide ranging appetite that sometimes include small house pets, Long Island will be primed for negative human/wildlife conforontations if proactive management does not take place. Therefore, identifying what habitat will best suit the Eastern Coyote on Long Island is of some importance. To this end it was decided to conduct a pilot analysis using the Hamlet of Water Mill, a small hamlet on the southeastern fork of Long Island. The Hamlet of Water Mill has a diverse landscape and recent confirmed Eastern coyote sightings. The landscape is a good mix of forested areas to the north, developed in the south/south east, wetlands dispersed throughout with agricultural land in the center of the hamlet. All these landcover types are typical of the northeast of the U.S making watermill a great choice for this preliminary research.

What is a Habitat Suitability Model?¶

A Type of Suitability model that asses the quality of habitat for a species of interest. The model answers the questions, What does a species need to survive and thrive in a given AOI? Where are these prime locations within the AOI? Conceptually components are identified that are believed to answer this question. The model results in a HSI (Habitat Suitability Index) Which is an arbitrary index set by the maker of the model (U.S Fish & Wildlife Service, 1981; ESM 103).

3 Main components identified for this model through review of relevant literature. Each component is described via habitat variables which are thought to be signficant contributors to the identified main components (backed by a literature review)

  1. Resource Availability
    • Forest Edge
    • Canopy Cover
  2. Cover & Reproduction
    • Land Cover
  3. Anthropogenic Disturbance
    • Distance to Roads
    • Building Density per unit area

Conceptual Model of the HSM

Methodology: Utilizing ArcPy to Create the Model¶

The structure of the model is such that each factor is calculated sepeartely and represented by a raster layer, with values from some arbitrary evaluation scale (1 - 100 was chosen here). The lower a score, the lower the excpected carrying capacity of the area and therefore less suitable habitat; a score of 1 or less means the habitat is not at all suitable, while a score of 100 means the area is highly suitable. After each factor is calculated, the rasters are added together and then divided by the number of total number of rasters (i.e. arithmetic mean). To start the needed modules are imported, we need both arcpy and the arcpy spatial analysis module (for working with rasters).

Before any modeling can begin, a land-cover raster must be sourced with acceptable accuracy and spatial resolution for the intended purpose. For this study a custom land-cover Raster was created with NAIP 1M Imagery using the NLCD 2011 Land-Cover Classifcation system (81% Overall accuracy, 76% Kappa). The simplest factor to create is the land-cover factor. This factor represents cover and reproduction within the model. First we bring it into the workspace and then it is reclassified to assign scores from the evaluation scale to each class. These scores are arbitrary and decided upon based on review of the relevant literature and/or expert opinion. A simple wrapper function is created that wraps of arcpys reclassify tool.

In [4]:
lc_ras = arcpy.Raster(r"coy_hsi_calculator\sample_data\water_mill_data.gdb\wm_lc_2017")

# remap values:
# 1  (Shadow) - 1
# 11 (Water) - 1
# 20 (Developed) - 10
# 21 (Developed, Open Space) - 40
# 30 (Barren Land) - 25
# 41 (Deciduous Forest) - 100
# 42 (Evergreen Forest) - 85
# 80 (Agricultural/Crop/Pasture) - 70
# 90 (Wetlands) - 55

def reclassify_wrapper(raster,remap_obj,field = "Value"):
    """
    Wrapper around the reclassify tool
    
    Args:
        raster: The raster to be reclassified
        remap_obj: a RemapValue or RemapRange object
        field: Field to act on, "Value" by default.
        
    Returns:
        A reclassified raster layer
  
    """
    
    reclass = Reclassify(raster,field,remap_obj)
    
    return reclass

lc_factor = reclassify_wrapper(lc_ras,lc_remap)

The next factor to calculate is Canopy cover, one of the habtiat variables relating to resource availability. Thicker canopies tend to have less understory vegetative cover and less small mammals that coyotes typically hunt. Canopy data was sourced from MRLC and has a spatial resolution of 30m. 30m is too coarse for this analysis but being the only available canopy cover dataset it was resampled to a resolution of 1m. Once resampled the next step is remap the raster values to be on the evaluation scale chosen. The workflow is identical to the process for creating the land-cover factor

In [5]:

# remap values:
# 0% to 10% - 50
# 11% to 30% - 100
# 31% to 50% - 75
# 51% to 70% - 50
# 71% to 100% - 25
canopy_factor = reclassify_wrapper(canopy_ras,canopy_remap)

In addition to canopy cover, forest edge was also identified as a habitat variable predictive of resource availability. In ecology something called edge effects occurs at the boundary of two or more habitats and numerous studies have shown that the Eastern Coyote takes advantage of these edge environments. Here we focus on two such environments, forested areas that edge agricultural areas, and forested areas that edge wetlands. Forest that edge agricultural areas allow the Eastern Coyote quick access to open areas for hunting small mammals typically found there (e.g. voles, rabbits, mice, etc). the Eastern Coyote will also likely take advantage of any human resources found. The coyotes can quickly retreat to the cover and safety of the forest, making this edge areas ideal. Forested areas that edge wetlands offer different oppurtunities, aside from quick escape to cover and access to denning areas, wetland and other natural edges may assist the Eastern coyote in hunting larger prey such as White Tail Deer. Coyotes have been shown chase deer into these environments where the wetlands may cut off their escape.

A function was created that calcules any edge area, not specific to this study. After calculating the edge areas the outputs are reclassified to the evaluation scale.

In [6]:
def calc_edge_area(outer_raster, inner_raster, radius=200):
    """
    Calculates an "Edge" raster; an area of interest (e.g. forest) 
    that edges a cover type of interest (e.g. wetlands, streets, etc). 
    
    Args:
        outer_raster: The habitat of interest that will make up the edge 
                      environment. This raster should be boolean, with
                      cells that are of the cover type of interest
                      (e.g. forest) having a score of 1 and all other cells
                      scored 0
        inner_raster: The inner habitat that the outer raster edges. Should
                      be a boolean raster where cells of interest are scored 1
                      and all others 0
        radius: Controls the width of the edge raster returned, by default 
                200 map units will be used.
                
    Returns:
        A raster of the edge area defined per the provided arguments
    
    Raises:
        ExecuteError: Arcpy will raise an execute error
    """
    
    # Run focal stats tool to find cells that "edge" the input cover_type
    # output raster will look similar to the original, but cells that edge the
    # cover will now have a score of 1 instead of 0                                  
    inner_edge = FocalStatistics(inner_raster,                 
                                        NbrRectangle(3, 3, "CELL"), 
                                        "MAXIMUM", 
                                        True) 
    
    # find cells in the outer edge raster that are adjacent the 
    # inner edge
    outer_cells_adj_inner = ((outer_raster == 1)&(inner_edge > 0))
    
    # Run focal stats to find cells within x map unit radius
    # of the boundary betweent he two habitat rasters
    nbr_circle = NbrCircle(radius,"MAP")
    within_x_of_edge = FocalStatistics(outer_cells_adj_inner, 
                                       nbr_circle, 
                                       statistics_type = "MAXIMUM", 
                                       ignore_nodata = True)
    
    
    # Create new raster where cells of the outer habitat are of the cover type
    # of interest (e.g. forest) and within x radius of the habitat boundary
    edge_raster = ((outer_raster == 1)&(within_x_of_edge > 0))
    
    return edge_raster

Lastly factors are calculated for anthropogenic disturbances. Pressure of humans will impact where coyotes den, hunt, reproduce and their active hours to some extent. It has been shown coyote abundance is negatively correlated with both distance to roads and building density. Two functions were developed to calculate these factors, each utilizes Arcpy's rescaling tool as the literature could not provide enough evidence to define categories for scoring. All we can say is that as distance to roads/streets decreases (habitat is closer to them) and building density increases (amount of buildings per a user defined area) we expect coyotes to be less abundant. The Rescaling tool works by utilizing a mathematical function to assign suitability values to an input raster on a continuous scale (ArcGIS Docs). The user choses a function that best predicates the relationship between the phenomenon being modeled and the variable to which the phenomenon responds to. Here it was decided that the function that best represent our factors are the simple "small" and "large" functions. Each of these functions has a midpoint and spread. Scoring changes once the midpoint is reached, with the change being function dependant (see code docs below); the spread controls how quickly the values will increase or decrease as they move from the midpoint.

The Small function is used when smaller input values are more preferred. In contrast, Large is used when larger input values are more preferred.

In [13]:
buildings = r"C:\Users\cvric\OneDrive\Desktop\coy_hsi_calculator\sample_data\water_mill_data.gdb\wm_buildings"
streets = r"C:\Users\cvric\OneDrive\Desktop\coy_hsi_calculator\sample_data\water_mill_data.gdb\wm_streets"

def rescale_wrapper(dist_layer,function,midpoint="#",
                    spread="#",scale_start=1,scale_end=100):
    """
    Wrapper around the rescale tool that limits the transformation
    functions used to "small" and "large". Only dist_layer and function
    are required; midpoint will default to the mean of the dist_layer, and
    spread to a value of 5.
    
    Args:
        dist_layer: The a raster layer that represents a disturbance factor.
        function: Transformation function to use (must be "small" or "large").
        midpoint: Values greater than midpoint decrease in preference("small").
                  Values greater than midpoint increase in preference("large").
        spread: How quickly values increase and decrease as they move from the
                midpoint.
        scale_start: The start of the evaluation scale (e.g. 1).
        scale_end: The end of the evaluation scale (e.g. 100).
    
    Returns:
        a rescaled raster layer
    
    """
        
    if function.lower() == "small":    
        transformation_function = TfSmall(midpoint, spread)
    if function.lower() == "large":
        transformation_function = TfLarge(midpoint, spread)

    reclass = RescaleByFunction(dist_layer, transformation_function, scale_start, scale_end)

    return reclass

def calc_building_factor(buildings,cellsize,radius,midpoint="#",
                         spread="#",scale_start=1,scale_end=100):
    """
    Calculates the building factor for the Eastern Coyote Habitat Suitability
    Model. Building points per the specified radius are calculated to gauge
    building density and the a rescale is performed.
    
    Args:
        buildings: Point or polygon features that represent buildings.
        radius: Radius used to calculate building density per unit area
        midpoint: Values greater than midpoint decrease in preference.
        spread: How quickly values increase and decrease as they move from the
                midpoint.
        scale_start: The start of the evaluation scale (e.g. 1).
        scale_end: The end of the evaluation scale (e.g. 100).
    
    Returns:
        The building factor for the model per the specified arguments
        
    Raises:
        Exception: Raised if a feature class of the wrong shapetype is provided
    
    """
    shape_type = arcpy.Describe(buildings).shapeType                                             
    if shape_type == 'Polygon':
        building_pts = arcpy.FeatureToPoint_management(buildings, 
                                                       r"in_memory\buildPts", 
                                                       "INSIDE")
    elif shape_type == 'Point':
        building_pts = buildings
        
    else:
        raise Exception("buildings must be polygon or point!")
        
        
    pt_density = PointDensity(building_pts, "NONE",cellsize, 
                              NbrCircle(radius,"MAP"))
    
    factor = rescale_wrapper(pt_density,"small",midpoint,
                             spread,scale_start,scale_end)
    
    arcpy.Delete_management(r"in_memory\buildPts")
                                
    return factor


def calc_street_factor(streets,cellsize,midpoint="#",
                       spread="#",scale_start=1,scale_end=100):
    """
    Calculates the street factor for the Eastern Coyote Habitat Suitability
    Model.Euclidean distance is calculated for cells in the raster, further
    a cell is from a street the higher it will be scored
    
    Args:
        streets: line feature representing streets/roads.
        cellsize: Cell size to use for euclidean distance calculation
        midpoint: Values greater than midpoint increase in preference.
        spread: How quickly values increase and decrease as they move from the
                midpoint.
        scale_start: The start of the evaluation scale (e.g. 1).
        scale_end: The end of the evaluation scale (e.g. 100).
    
    Returns:
        The building factor for the model per the specified arguments
        

    """

    dt_streets = EucDistance(streets,cell_size=cellsize)
    
    factor = rescale_wrapper(dt_streets,"large",midpoint,
                             spread,scale_start,scale_end)
    
    return factor

Here the default values are used for the parameters relative to the rescaling, which was found to deliver a reasonable result. A radius of 8200 map units (feet here) is used (yields an area of ~ 20km^2); this is a reasonable assumption for an Eastern coyotes home range within the AOI. The land cover raster cell sized is used here (cell size should be continuious throughout the model), the defaults are kept for the evaluation scale parameters.

The last step is to calculate the final HSI and then clip the result to the area of interest. Before the score can be calculated however the Con and IsNull tools are used to ensure that each factor raster edge remains intact, converting any no data values to 0 instead.

In [24]:
factors = [for_edge_wet_factor,for_edge_ag_factor,building_factor,
               street_factor,lc_factor,canopy_factor]
    
# Ensures that resulting raster edges remain intact
# converts no data values to 0
factors = [Con(IsNull(factor),0,factor) for factor in factors]

hsi = sum(factors)/6

# clip the resulting hsi raster to the area of interest
desc = arcpy.Describe(aoi).extent
extent = "{} {} {} {}".format(desc.XMin,desc.YMin,desc.XMax,desc.YMax)
coyote_hsm = arcpy.Clip_management(hsi,extent,wks+r"\coyote_hsi",aoi,"0","ClippingGeometry","MAINTAIN_EXTENT")

Upon inspection of the resulting model, you can see that it is reasonable given the defined parameters and what we know about the area of interest. The highest scores are disturbed forested areas that edge agricultural and/or wetlands and are far from anthropogenic disturbances. More interesting than result is the models reusability and the prospect of adjustments as more information becomes available. The hope is that an expert/researcher utilizes the model and makes adjustments as they see fit. For example, the model could be used to decide where the best location is to set up scented camera traps or transects to look for scat as part of a study to calculate abundance. The results of such a study could be used to calibrate the model further, maybe we see that there is a definite distance range of which no matter how good the habitat is coyotes will not populate it if it's within that distance of streets or dense building centers. Maybe we see that wetlands are more correlated with coyote abundance then previously thought and therefore should recieve a higher score within the model.
